igo de Reinosa, Jones makes a strong case for revising the belief, long held by literary critics and linguists, that white appropriations and representations of habla de negros language are "racist buffoonery" or stereotype. Instead, Jones shows black characters who laugh, sing, and shout, ultimately combating the violent desire of white supremacy. By placing early modern Iberia in conversation with discourses on African diaspora studies, Jones showcases how black Africans and their descendants who built communities in early modern Spain were rendered legible in performative literary texts.Accessibly written and theoretically sophisticated, Jones's groundbreaking study elucidates the ways that habla de negros animated black Africans' agency, empowered their resistance, and highlighted their African cultural retentions. This must-read book on identity building, performance, and race will captivate audiences across disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican diaspora in literature. 0aTheaterzSpainxAfrican influencesxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheaterzSpainxAfrican influencesxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheaterzSpainxAfrican influencesxHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271083940zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271083940423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271083940/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE 